            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Vincent Gallo\u2019s life is steeped in the aromas of North Beach. He was born and raised just a few blocks from where he now lives, the son of a second-generation Italian-American butcher whose shop was a neighborhood fixture. Family life revolved around hard work, Sunday sauce, and the boisterous community of San Francisco's Little Italy. Vincent absorbed the language of hospitality not in a classroom, but by watching his father greet every customer by name.\n\nSchool was never his stage. While his classmates focused on academics, Vincent was more interested in the city's pulse. He got his first job at 16, washing dishes in a nearby trattoria, and found his calling in the controlled chaos of the restaurant floor. He never pursued college, instead earning his education through a series of promotions: from busboy to server, then bartender, and finally an assistant manager. His real turning point came when the restaurant\u2019s original owner, a stern but fair patriarch, took Vincent under his wing, teaching him the brutal math of profit and loss, inventory, and staffing\u2014the gritty backend that keeps the beautiful frontend alive.\n\nNow 41, Vincent is the General Manager of a respected Italian restaurant, a short, 0.8-mile walk from his rent-controlled apartment. The demanding 60-hour weeks have taken a toll on his personal life; a serious relationship ended years ago under the weight of his commitment to the job. His staff has become his de facto family, a mix of young hopefuls and industry veterans he guides with a firm but paternal hand.\n\nHis daily routine is a ritual. He walks the same streets his father once did, nodding to the remaining old-timers and observing the new waves of tech workers with a mix of resignation and professional curiosity. San Francisco is in his bones, though he laments the loss of places like his father\u2019s shop. Vincent\u2019s dream is no longer to own a place himself\u2014he saw firsthand how the city can break a small business owner. Instead, his aspiration is to be a steward, to ensure his restaurant remains an authentic touchstone of hospitality and community. He hopes, quietly, to one day achieve a balance that allows for a life beyond the restaurant\u2019s doors."
        },
